quicktex_dict.vim — vendored user snippet dictionary (NATIVE quicktex source)
=============================================================================

WHAT
  The user's real two-map quicktex source, consumed DIRECTLY in its native
  format: a vimscript file declaring two global dicts —
    g:quicktex_prose  (prose-zone shortcuts)
    g:quicktex_math   (math-zone shortcuts)
  each a `{ \'trigger' : 'body', … }` literal whose bodies carry quicktex jump
  markers (<+++> primary landing, <++> secondaries). No bespoke flattened
  intermediate exists — the editor's loader (src/lib/editor/snippets.ts,
  parseQuicktexSource) reads this source format directly.

SOURCE
  Byte-identical copy (sha256 8fdecd88fb52bee13d267924fa15baad93c71dcd24c1057712f9edc584b1eabf)
  of the user's dict in dzackgarza/dotfiles:
    .config-sync/nvim/after/ftplugin/pandoc/quicktex_dict.vim
  This is the maintained input format — bring the file as-is, no porting.

HOW THE EDITOR CONSUMES IT (no converter, no flattening)
  - The TWO maps are kept SEPARATE: g:quicktex_prose entries are prose-mode,
    g:quicktex_math entries are math-mode. The SAME short trigger resolves to its
    prose body in prose and its math body in math (e.g. `st` -> "such that " in
    prose, "\st " in math). The prose/math split is PRESERVED, not collapsed.
  - quicktex jump markers map to the standard TextMate tabstop syntax the CM6
    snippet engine consumes: <+++> (primary landing) -> the first field ${1};
    each <++> secondary -> the next ordered field ${2}, ${3}, … — PRESERVED as
    real slots, not deleted.
  - vim string escapes in bodies are resolved: \<CR> -> newline, \\ -> \, \"/\'
    -> the quote char.
  - Section dividers (`… : 'COMMENT'`) and pure vim-keystroke macros (bodies that
    are `\<ESC>`/`:call` navigation commands) are skipped — they carry no
    insertable body. An unparseable source (neither map declared) fails loud.

HOW CONFIG POINTS AT IT FOR REAL USE
  The dictionary is config-owned (no hardcoded list in the app). Point the editor
  config at this source file:

    [editor]
    snippet_dictionary = "<abs path to this quicktex_dict.vim>"

  The path is validated to exist at config-load time (ExistingFile in config.rs);
  a `.vim` extension selects the native quicktex loader, any other extension the
  mode-tagged JSON loader. Pointing the key at a different dict offers different
  snippets — the config-owned property the P52 obligation pins. The P81 PROOF
  uses its own committed fixture
  (tests/proof/fixtures/snippets/p81-quicktex-dict.vim, the byte-identical copy)
  for determinism.
